# EXCERCISE 1

import pandas as pd
data = pd.read_csv("gap.tsv", sep='\t')
graph = data.plot.scatter(x='year',y='lifeExp')
graph.set_title("World Wide Life Expectancy Over The Years")
graph.set_xlabel('Year')
graph.set_ylabel('Life Expectancy')
Out[ ]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Life Expectancy')

The graph above shows the scatter plot of all the data of the various countries' life expectancies with the x axis being the year and the y axis being the life expectancy.

Question 1

There appears to be a general trend of the life expectancy going up over time; the highest life expectancy and lowest life expectancy for each year increases as time goes on (aside from outliers).

Question 2

The distribution looks as if the average life span is increasing every year. We can see the bulge representing the majority increasing. As time goes on, the life expectancy begins to skew towards the maximum especially after the year 1987.

Question 3

Yes I would reject the null hypothesis of no reationship between life expectancy and year, because it looks as if there is a definite increase in average life expectancy as the year increases.

Question 4

It would probably look similar to the existing graph because since the linear regression model would average the extremes of high and low life expectancies over the years, meaning the years with lower averages would have negative residuals and those with higher averages would have positive residuals.

Question 5

The model, if the null hypothesis is actually true, should instead have all of the bulges in the same spot on all the years, as the residual values would be near zero.

import numpy as np
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
x = np.array(data.year).reshape((-1,1))
y = data.lifeExp
model = LinearRegression().fit(x,y)
print(model.score(x,y))
print(model.intercept_)
print(model.coef_)

# Question 6

import statsmodels.formula.api as sm
statmodel = sm.ols(formula="lifeExp ~ year ", data=data).fit()
print(statmodel.summary())

Question 6

It seems that according to the model, life expectancy increases by .32 years every year.

Question 7

The p-value given in the summary is 0 (or so close to 0 that it is approximately the same) so that means we reject the null hypothesis that there is no relationship between year and life expectancy.

Question 8

Yes, the plot matches exactly as predicted. We can see on this graph that during the earlier years (the years with lower life expectancy), the residuals are grouping below 0, and then as the years pass, they slowly move to become grouped above 0.

# EXCERCISE 5

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

data_asia = data[data['continent'] == "Asia"]
data_eu = data[data['continent'] == "Europe"]
data_africa = data[data['continent'] == "Africa"]
data_americas = data[data['continent'] == "Americas"]
data_oce = data[data['continent'] == "Oceania"]

graph_asia = data_asia.plot.scatter(x='year',y='lifeExp').set_title("Life Expectancy Over the Years in Asia")
b, a = np.polyfit(x=data_asia['year'],y=data_asia['lifeExp'],deg=1)
xseq = np.linspace(1950,2010,num=100)
plt.plot(xseq, a+b*xseq, color="k", lw=2.5)

graph_eu = data_eu.plot.scatter(x='year',y='lifeExp').set_title("Life Expectancy Over the Years in Europe")
b, a = np.polyfit(x=data_eu['year'],y=data_eu['lifeExp'],deg=1)
xseq = np.linspace(1950,2010,num=100)
plt.plot(xseq, a+b*xseq, color="k", lw=2.5)

graph_africa = data_africa.plot.scatter(x='year',y='lifeExp').set_title("Life Expectancy Over the Years in Africa")
b, a = np.polyfit(x=data_africa['year'],y=data_africa['lifeExp'],deg=1)
xseq = np.linspace(1950,2010,num=100)
plt.plot(xseq, a+b*xseq, color="k", lw=2.5)

graph_americas = data_americas.plot.scatter(x='year',y='lifeExp').set_title("Life Expectancy Over the Years in Americas")

xseq = np.linspace(1950,2010,num=100)
